In article <2tvm8q$h5q@news.iastate.edu>,
Warren vonRoeschlaub <kv07@iastate.edu> wrote:
>  What prevents a person from taking the public key for an RSA
>encryption, encoding a message, and then trying every d until the
>message is decoded?  Since decoding is O(n^3) and there are only n
>possibilities for d you get an O(n^4) method of cracking d.  Sure,
>there might be a huge constant out in front, but how huge does it
>have to be to make this harder than trying to factor n?  This could
>probably be done even faster by starting at n-sqrt(n)+2 and going
>down since d is usually large.

There are b^n possibilities for d, where b is the unit you are using
to measure n (i.e. b==2 if you are saying "n bit key", or b==10 if
you are saying "n digit key").  So with decoding at O(n^3) this means
you have O(n^3 * b^n) possibilities for this naive brute-force search.

		--Ken Pizzini
